here,because where I am folded,there I am a lie.\n\n- Rainer Maria Rilke, Rilke's Book of Hours: Love Poems to God\n|\nknow what you want, work to get it, then value it once you have it.\n\n- Nora Roberts, Morrigan's Cross\n|\nLife is not a puzzle to solve. Stop, Enjoy the Journey!-RVM\n\n- RVM\n|\nHope is a good breakfast, but it is a bad supper.\n\n- Francis\n|\nInstead of complaining, discover ways, tactics and tricks on how to reach out to people\n\n- Sunday\n|\nAll Dogs Go To Heaven? Sorry, kids. It's only the dogs who've accepted Christ.\n\n- Stephen Colbert, I Am America\n|\nYou either bend, or you break. Suppress your ego to stay happy.\n\n- Manoj Arora, Happiness Unlimited: How to be happy always\n|\nDead people can be our heroes because they cant disappoint us later; they only improve over time, as we forget more and more about them.\n\n- Veronica Roth, Four: A Divergent Story Collection\n|\nThere are three stages in scientific discovery. First, people deny that it is true, then they deny that it is important; finally they credit the wrong person.\n\n- Bill Bryson, A Short History of Nearly Everything\n|\nLet your love for book grow, as your confidence grows.\n\n- Liza\n|\nDifficult times revel true friends but also the unfaithful in your life. Be attentive always, but especially during tough times.\n\n- Mensah\n|\nThere's nothing that keeps its youth, so far as I know, but a tree and truth.\n\n- Oliver Wendell Holmes Sr., The Deacon's Masterpiece or the Wonderful One-Hoss Shay\n|\nPerhaps life is like an hour glass, with dear ones the sand that slips from the upper glass--the earth--into the second--eternity.\n\n- Margaret George, Elizabeth I\n|\nKnowing beauty is not what can be described but felt, upon looking at something beautiful.\n\n- Benjamin\n|\nAll art is abstract, because art is an abstraction of the truth.\n\n- Milford\n|\nA young writer is easily tempted by the allusive and ethereal and ironic and reflective, but the declarative is at the bottom of most good writing.\n\n- Garrison\n|\nTo have my hopes raised and dashed again, it's like cold steel twisting in my gut.\n\n- Paula Hawkins, The Girl on the Train\n|\nMost often, what I don’t know will have a vastly greater bearing on my life that what I do know.\n\n- Craig\n|\nI saw no way out but to dive right in, to a good book.\n\n- Genesis\n|\nIf you've got nothing to dance about, find a reason to sing.\n\n- Melody\n|\nIf I were to vote, I would intentionally vote for the goofiest candidate. It is my theory that when the people can outwit the leader, the more respected their voices will be.\n\n- Criss Jami, Killosophy\n|\nBak stood a moment, as though considering whether the sum total of their shared working life was ending in a minus or a plus.\n\n- Jussi Adler-Olsen, Disgrace\n|\nHope is important because it can make the present moment less difficult to bear. If we believe that tomorrow will be better, we can bear a hardship today.\n\n- Thich Nhat Hanh, Peace Is Every Step: The Path of Mindfulness in Everyday Life\n|\nInitially they waited with hope, but as each hour passed, hope slipped away like the wind, the wind that as a small boy Ethan had once tried to capture with his tiny fingers.\n\n- K. Martin Beckner, A Million Doorways\n|\nYour gifts, talents, and calling will help you to know what you must do.\n\n- Sunday Adelaja, How To Become Great Through Time Conversion: Are you wasting time, spending time or investing time?\n|\nIf seek the light of knowledge of God, we know how to live.\n\n- Lailah\n|\nAs the Weaver, so is the Thread\n\n- Louise Blackwick, Vivian Amberville - The Weaver of Odds\n|\nWhen every situation which life can offer is turned to the profit of spiritual growth, no situation can really be a bad one.\n\n- Paul\n|\nYou don't judge a tree by the name it Wears, you judge a tree by the fruit it Bears.\n\n- RVM\n|\nReality doesn't impress me. I only believe in intoxication, in ecstasy, and when ordinary life shackles me, I escape, one way or another. No more walls.\n\n- Anaïs Nin, Incest: From a Journal of Love\n|\nTo know yourself, you must first sacrifice the illusion that already you do.\n\n- Vironika\n|\nI took the volume to a table, opened its soft, ivory pages... and fell into it as into a pool during dry season.\n\n- Janet Fitch, White Oleander\n|\nIt's not about what I SEE for our future, or humanity; It's about what I DO for our future and humanity.\n\n- Steve\n|\nLearn everything you can, anytime you can, from anyone you can, there will always come a time when you will be grateful you did.\n\n- Sarah\n|\nAnd in the end,she left a scarand I knew that washow she wanted tobe remembered.She wanted to leaveher mark in theworldwithout gettingher heart tooattached to it.\n\n- Robert M. Drake, Black Butterfly\n|\nWe remember the past, live in the present, and write the future.\n\n- Shaun David Hutchinson, We Are the Ants\n|\nOne breath taken completely; one poem, fully written, fully read - in such a moment, anything can happen.\n\n- Jane Hirshfield, Nine Gates: Entering the Mind of Poetry\n|\nright in this moment, I can´t even remember what unhappy feels like.\n\n- Maggie Stiefvater, Shiver\n|\nYou were made for a particular purpose, but you can be anything you want. Anything, including that.\n\n- Sylvain Neuvel, Waking Gods\n|\nWhile you were busy working on your ego, she was busy working on her soul.\n\n- Melody  Lee, Moon Gypsy\n|\nTo fail is nothing, unless you continue to ignore Cosmic Ordering.\n\n- Stephen Richards, Cosmic Ordering Guide\n|\nFreely chosen, discipline is absolute freedom.\n\n- Ron\n|\nShall any gazer see with mortal eyes,Or any searcher know by mortal mind,Veil after veil will lift--but there must be Veil upon veil behind.\n\n- Edwin Arnold, The Light of Asia\n|\nYou would not enjoy Nietzsche, sir. He is fundamentally unsound.\n\n- P.G. Wodehouse, Carry on, Jeeves\n|\nWhen the door of opportunity of your storehouse opens for you, let faith and hope enter first. When your 